    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Protostellar discs are widely observed, but simply angular momentum conservation cannot explain their formation. This is because the typical angular momentum is not enough to overcome the observed magnetic tension force; this is the so-called “magnetic braking catastrophe”. However the braking efficiency depends on how well magnetic field lines can couple with gas.  Based on the MHD induction equation, good coupling (“flux freezing”) is a reasonable approximation only at large scales (e.g., cloud scale). At small scales, L’, ambipolar diffusion is likely to play a role and thus field lines and gas will decouple from each other. If L’ is comparable with the disc-formation scale, ambipolar diffusion will help to release the magnetic brake. ALMA offers the first opportunity to directly probe L’, a critical parameter to help understanding disc formation.</prp:abstract>
